        <prompt>John W. Davis's 1924 presidential nomination reflected:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Party unity</option>
            <option letter="b">Deep divisions in the Democratic Party</option>
            <option letter="c">Progressive victory</option>
            <option letter="d">Popular support</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>John W. Davis's nomination as the Democratic presidential candidate in 1924 reflected deep divisions within the Democratic Party. His selection came only after a bitter convention fight requiring 103 ballots, demonstrating the split between urban progressives and rural conservatives. As a compromise candidate satisfying neither faction, Davis's campaign struggled against incumbent Calvin Coolidge.</explanation>
